---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import { SITE } from "../data/site.js";

const title = "Methodology & Editorial Standards — KakouCalc";
const description =
  "How KakouCalc's calculators are built, verified and kept current — the formulas, the independent automated testing, the data sources, and our editorial standards.";

// A WebPage with a real dateModified is an honest, supported signal. No invented
// author or rating — the publisher is the site, and every claim below is checkable.
const pageSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "WebPage",
  name: title,
  description,
  url: new URL("/methodology", Astro.site).href,
  dateModified: SITE.updatedISO,
  publisher: { "@type": "Organization", name: SITE.org, url: Astro.site?.href },
};
---

<Base
  title={title}
  description={description}
  breadcrumbs={[{ name: "Home", url: "/" }, { name: "Methodology" }]}
  jsonLd={[pageSchema]}
>
  <section class="calc-guide doc-page">
    <div class="guide-block">
      <h1>Methodology &amp; editorial standards</h1>
      <p>
        KakouCalc publishes {`free financial calculators`} covering loans, investing, retirement,
        credit, and more. Because these are money decisions, accuracy is the whole product. This page
        explains exactly how the calculators are built, how their math is verified, where the reference
        data comes from, and how the content is reviewed — so you can judge the numbers for yourself.
      </p>
      <p class="guide-aside">Last reviewed {SITE.updated}.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="guide-block">
      <h2>Standard, published formulas</h2>
      <p>
        Every calculator uses the standard, textbook formula for its problem — not a proprietary or
        approximated one. Loan and mortgage figures come from the ordinary amortization formula; time
        value of money uses the same present-value and future-value equations as a financial calculator;
        option prices use Black-Scholes; stock valuations use the Gordon growth and multi-stage dividend
        discount models. The math is the math the field already agrees on.
      </p>
      <p>
        Calculations run entirely in your browser. Nothing you type is sent to a server, stored, or
        shared — there is no account, and no analytics on your inputs.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="guide-block">
      <h2>Independent, automated verification</h2>
      <p>
        This is the part most calculator sites can't claim. Every calculator is checked by an automated
        test suite that computes each result a <strong>second, independent way</strong> and confirms the
        two agree — so a mistake can't hide by agreeing with itself. The independent check is either a
        formula typed from a finance textbook, a brute-force month-by-month simulation, or a
        canonical published value.
      </p>
      <p>
        For example, the Black-Scholes calculator is checked against the textbook benchmark
        (S=100, K=100, T=1, r=5%, σ=20% → call price 10.4506); loan interest is checked against a
        month-by-month amortization simulation; and every calculator is confirmed to return a real,
        finite figure rather than an error on ordinary inputs. The suite currently runs
        <strong>hundreds of individual checks</strong>, and the site is not shipped unless they all pass.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="guide-block">
      <h2>Reference data &amp; how current it is</h2>
      <p>
        A few calculators depend on outside data, which we label rather than let you assume is live:
      </p>
      <dl class="guide-glossary">
        <div class="guide-term">
          <dt>Inflation (CPI)</dt>
          <dd>US Consumer Price Index (CPI-U) annual averages. A year's figure is an annual average, so it only appears once that year is complete.</dd>
        </div>
        <div class="guide-term">
          <dt>Exchange rates</dt>
          <dd>Reference rates refreshed at build time and shown with an "as of" date in the Currency Converter. Rates move continuously between updates — treat them as indicative and check a live source before acting.</dd>
        </div>
        <div class="guide-term">
          <dt>Tax brackets &amp; RMD tables</dt>
          <dd>US federal figures, stamped with their tax year. Tax rules change annually and vary by state — confirm the current year's figures for your situation.</dd>
        </div>
      </dl>
    </div>

    <div class="guide-block">
      <h2>Review, updates &amp; corrections</h2>
      <p>
        Each calculator guide carries a "reviewed" date, and this page carries the site's last-reviewed
        date ({SITE.updated}). When we find or are told about an error, we fix the underlying formula —
        which the verification suite then locks in so the same mistake can't return — and update the
        date. Found something that looks wrong? Tell us at{" "}
        <a href={`mailto:${SITE.contactEmail}`}>{SITE.contactEmail}</a> and we'll check it.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="guide-block">
      <h2>Educational information, not financial advice</h2>
      <p>
        KakouCalc is a set of tools and explanations for learning and planning. It is not financial,
        investment, tax, or legal advice, and it can't account for your full personal situation. The
        results rest on the assumptions you enter — real rates, returns, taxes, and fees vary. For
        decisions that matter, verify the figures and talk to a qualified professional.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="guide-block">
      <h2>Who is behind KakouCalc</h2>
      <p>
        KakouCalc is an independent, free financial-calculator publisher. Read more on the{" "}
        <a href="/about">About page</a>, or reach the team at{" "}
        <a href={`mailto:${SITE.contactEmail}`}>{SITE.contactEmail}</a>.
      </p>
      {
        SITE.reviewer && (
          <p><strong>{SITE.reviewer}</strong></p>
        )
      }
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
